  "doc_id": "59076",
  "text": "Today sexually active or pregnant unmarried women are not killed, as sometimes happened in the past, but they might be pressured to the point where they consider suicide. [CITATION_1] Illicit pregnancies are kept quiet, within the family, and very often attempts are made to secure a marriage with the father. [CITATION_2] If a hastily arranged marriage fails to take place, the pregnancy might be secretly terminated. As a result, there is a 90% illegal abortion rate despite abortion being legal in India. [CITATION_3] Much of Indian custom is family based. For a young woman, having premarital sexual relations can affect the social ranking of her entire family, including any unmarried siblings. [CITATION_4] These siblings might be considered unmarriageable, or in many instances, their marriages will require a much larger dowry. [CITATION_5] When families are arranging a marriage, they make sure the family that their son or daughter is marrying into has a good reputation, which can be translated to be no history of premarital pregnancies or premarital sex. [CITATION_6] In towns (as opposed to the rural areas) some love marriages and cross-caste marriages do occur. In these cases, parental agreement is still important and cross-caste marriages often take place between castes at a similar hierarchical level. [CITATION_7] For many Indian women, lack of sex education makes their intercourse experiences painful. [CITATION_8] Sexual encounters are taught to be a duty and are not meant to be pleasurable for the woman. Mothers teach their daughters that their role in life is to make their husbands happy and not to question. Men are not educated about contraception. [CITATION_9] Often neither men nor women understand the concept of ovulation and timing pregnancies. The exception might be Indian women who attend Pre-Cana (premarital instructions given to Catholic Indian couples) classes that teach sex education before marriage. Generally, women are not educated about contraceptive options until after the first child. For this reason most couples have their first child within the first year of marriage. [CITATION_10] The birth of a healthy first child is used to assure both families that the marriage is a good match and that the couple is in good health. [CITATION_11] If a child is not born after the first or second year of marriage, couples are commonly sent to fertility specialists.",
